<br>
The architect tries to force Neo to make choices based on logic. Think the idea they were trying to convey is that love tends to defy logic, so Neo is making choices that he shouldnt make, logically, because of his love for Trinity. I think the idea of &quot;Love defies Logic&quot; will be the key to destroying the matrix in the 3rd movie somehow.<br>
<br>
So the whole grand matrix scheme, which is based on a series of logical choices isn't going as planned. Neo simply wont follow the logical path. <br>
<br>
I had a few problems with the movie also. The combat music just did not &quot;fit&quot; at all. Some scenes took way too long, &quot;aka, the xion tribal dance scene&quot; and some of the fight scenes didn't seem necessary. &quot;aka, the weapons fight scene with the french man's goons&quot;, although, they did display superhuman abilities, so maybe the matrix evolved some as Neo did, or maybe Neo only meant to delay them, dunno, but it seemed like he was fighting people he should have dispatched effortlessly.<br>
<br>
As in the first movie, I enjoyed the character of the Oracle. I also liked the Keymaster. I'm inclined to agree with the &quot;matrix in a matrix&quot; theory, ala the 13th floor. (B movie with a similar story) For some reason though, something is bugging me. The architect keeps making references to &quot;the anomoly&quot;, which we are supposed to think, is Neo. I'm starting to think it's Agent Smith. He is the only being in the matrix to transcend to the xion world, to my knowledge. Just a hunch.<br>
<br>
