<br>
Star Wars.<br>
As a movie, it stood on its own.  At the end of the movie, evil (DeathStar) was vanquished, and all was right with the galaxy.  Except that Vader was still lurking around.  The ending leaves us thinking &quot;what could happen next?&quot; but with peace of mind.<br>
If Star Wars had sucked ass, most of us would never have heard of it, and it would be sitting on a dusty video store shelf next to Solarbabies. And it wouldn't matter how many sequels and prequels Lucas wrote. But people did like Star Wars, and Lucas was bank rolled to create Empire.<br>
Empire is not a movie on its own.  Imagine somebody who's never heard of the Star Wars trilogy renting and watching JUST Empire.  They would have sooo many questions about what came before and what came after. And they would return it thinking it was a crappy movie for having such a downer for an ending.  The ending of Empire did nothing but lead up to Jedi.<br>
Jedi put a cap on the story line.  The evil is definitely destroyed this time.  Lucas would have a hard time convincing people that the Emperor had an escape pod down at the bottom of the shaft which Vader threw him.<br>
<br>
So far The Matrix is following the same pattern.<br>
The Matrix was a fine movie on its own.  Evil (Smith, and presumably all Agents) is vanquished.  Except the Matrix is still lurking around.  Neo flies off, leaving us thinking &quot;what could happen next?&quot; but with peace of mind.<br>
Imagine somebody seeing JUST Matrix: Reloaded.  At the end of the movie: &quot;Hey, there's that guy the Agent Smith jumped into lying next to Neo.&quot; [CUT TO BLACK] <br>
And if Revolutions doesn't end the story line, I think there's gonna be rioting in the streets.<br>
<br>
I've thought of a few other movies that follow the same pattern:<br>
<br>
Back to the Future<br>
The first one did well on its own.  At the end evil is vanquished (in this case &quot;evil&quot; is the problems the Delorian creates).  Except the Delorian is still lurking around.  They all fly off in the Delorian, leaving us thinking &quot;what could happen next?&quot; but with peace of mind.  (I don't think they originally planned on making sequels, despite that it said &quot;to be continued&quot;)<br>
BttF2 ended with Doc getting zapped into the Wild West, and even showed clips from BttF3.<br>
At the end of BttF3 the &quot;evil&quot; Delorian is destroyed, thus ending the story.  They even put &quot;The End&quot; at the end.<br>
<br>
X-Men<br>
Again, this one did well on its own.  It ended with evil (Magneto) being vanquished, but still lurking around.  And Mystique posing as the Senator left us thinking.<br>
X2 probably could stand up on its own better than others.  It ended with Jean getting washed away (a definite downer).  But if you noticed the faint orange glow in the water where she fell, and know a bit about Marvel comics, you can see the &quot;Pheonix&quot; rising, leading up to the next (but maybe not last) movie.<br>
<br>
Terminator<br>
It did well on its own.  Evil (the Terminator, duh) was vanquished.  But the future is still uncertain.<br>
T2 again did okay on its own, but the ending definitely left the door open for another movie, what with them driving down a dark road. (BtW they had created a happy ending with Sarah playing with her grand children in the park, but it didn't go over well with test audiences.)<br>
I've seen teasers for T3.  The robots are in the process of taking over the world.  If the evil isn't permenantly destroyed after this one, we might see T4 and T5.<br>
<br>
I feel the Star Wars prequels are a trilogy in themselves.  Of course the feeling of continuation is a bit forced since we're expecting them, and we pretty much know whats going to happen.<br>
Phantom Menace ended with evil (droids and the Federation) being vanquished.  But the Emperor/Palpatine(sp?) is still lurking around.<br>
At the end of Attack of the Clones we're just waiting to see how Anakin finally turns over to the dark side, or what's the circumstances of Luke and Leia's birth.<br>
I suppose the end of Episode 3 wouldn't see the final destruction of evil. /shrug<br>
<br>
<br>
So the trilogy formula:<br>
1st movie - stands well on its own; evil is dealt with but not permanently<br>
2nd movie - a lead in to the 3rd movie<br>
3rd movie - the end of the story line; evil is wiped out for good<br>
<br>
I noticed a few trilogies that don't fit the formula:<br>
Beverly Hills Cop, Indiana Jones, Jurassic Park, Evil Dead, Lord of the Rings<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
While watching Star Wars: Episode 2 - Attack of the Clones, I noticed a pattern in all the Star Wars movies.  There's a seperation of Jedi fighting (with light sabers), and everybody else fighting (with blasters and space ships).<br>
Star Wars: Vader &amp; ObiWan dueling while everybody else blows up the DeathStar<br>
Empire: Luke &amp; Vader dueling while Han gets frozen in carbonite<br>
Jedi: Luke, Vader &amp; Emperor dueling while Ewoks and everybody else blow up DeathStar2<br>
Phantom Menace: QuiGonJinn, ObiWan &amp; DarthMaul dueling while JarJar and Anakin destroy the droids and Federation<br>
Attack of the Clones: Yoda &amp; CountDooku/DarthTyranus dueling while the cloned storm troopers destroy the droids<br>
Episode 3: Obiwan &amp; Anikan/Vader dueling while ????<br>
<br>
There's a similar seperation in the first two Matrix movies.<br>
Matrix: Neo is fighting Agent Smith in the matrix while the Nebekenezzer(sp?) is being attacked by the squiddy in the real world<br>
Reloaded: The Architect is making Neo choose doors in the matrix while Zion is getting attacked by the squiddies in the real world (we don't see the battle)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
<br>
Matrix Joke<br>
<br>
Why can't you eat soup in the Matrix?<br>
<br>
